Chapter 4 Regression - Linear models¶

1. Multiple Linear Regression¶

Regression is a method used to build a mathematical relationship between predictors (independent variables) and a dependent (response) variable.

Multiple regression extends simple linear regression by allowing more than one independent (explanatory) variable. While simple regression uses a single predictor, multiple regression fits a model for one dependent variable based on multiple predictors. This makes it a powerful tool in predictive analytics and statistical modeling. By incorporating multiple predictors, analysts can better understand the relationships among variables and improve predictive performance. Multiple regression is widely applied in fields such as finance, marketing, healthcare, and environmental sciences.

Applications of Multiple Regression¶

Economics and Finance¶

  • Stock Price Prediction: Estimate stock prices using predictors such as interest rates, market indices, and company financials.
  • Economic Forecasting: Predict GDP growth, inflation rates, or unemployment using macroeconomic indicators.

Environmental Sciences¶

  • Climate Modeling: Forecast climate patterns, temperature changes, or environmental outcomes using meteorological and geographic variables.
  • Air Quality Prediction: Predict pollution levels from emissions, weather conditions, and geographic features.

General Model¶

$$ y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{1,i} + \beta_2 x_{2,i} + \ldots + \beta_p x_{p,i} + \varepsilon_{i} $$

where:

  • $y_i$ = dependent variable
  • $x_{1,i}, x_{2,i}, \ldots, x_{p,i}$ = independent variables
  • $\beta_0, \beta_1, \ldots, \beta_p$ = regression coefficients
  • $\varepsilon_i$ = error term

Note: "Linear" refers to the linearity in parameters, not necessarily in predictors.

Least Squares Estimation (Matrix Form)¶

$$ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} = (X^T X)^{-1} X^T Y $$

where:

  • $\boldsymbol{\beta}$: vector of coefficients (including the intercept $\beta_0$)
  • $X$: design matrix of size $n \times (p+1)$
  • $Y$: vector of observed dependent variable values

Prediction for a new case¶

In predictive modeling, a fitted multiple regression model is used to generate point predictions and uncertainty intervals for new cases.

Let the fitted model be $$ \hat{y}_i = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 x_{1,i} + \cdots + \hat{\beta}_p x_{p,i}. $$ For a new feature vector $x_{\text{new}} = (x_{1,\text{new}}, \ldots, x_{p,\text{new}})$, define the augmented vector $$ \mathbf{x}_{\text{new}} = (1, x_{1,\text{new}}, \ldots, x_{p,\text{new}})^\top. $$ Then the predicted value is $$ \hat{y}_{\text{new}} = \mathbf{x}_{\text{new}}^\top \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}. $$

We will use the airquality dataset in R:

  • Source: New York State Department of Conservation (ozone data) and the National Weather Service (meteorological data), cited in Chambers et al. (1985).
  • Description: Daily air quality measurements in New York, from May to September 1973.
  • Structure: A data frame with 153 observations on 6 variables.

Feature Interaction¶

When a model makes a prediction based on two features, the prediction can be decomposed into four components:

  1. Constant term
    Represents the baseline prediction when both features are at their reference values (often the intercept).

  2. First feature effect
    Contribution to the prediction attributed solely to the first feature, while holding the second feature constant.

  3. Second feature effect
    Contribution to the prediction attributed solely to the second feature, while holding the first feature constant.

  4. Interaction term
    Captures the combined effect of both features on the prediction, beyond their individual contributions.
    In other words, it represents the change in the prediction that results when the two features are varied together, accounting for the main effects of each feature.
    The interaction effect occurs when the effect of one feature depends on the value of the other feature.

Feature Engineering¶

Feature engineering is a crucial step in data science that involves transforming raw data into more informative and useful inputs (features) for machine learning algorithms. This preprocessing step includes selecting, creating, modifying, and combining variables to enhance the predictive power of models. High-quality features often make a bigger difference to predictive accuracy than the choice of model itself.

Common Techniques¶

  • Feature selection
    Identify and select the most relevant features from the raw data, which can improve model performance by removing noise or irrelevant variables.

  • Model selection criteria
    To choose the best model, commonly used strategies include Mallows’ $C_p$, Akaike Information Criterion (AIC), and Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC).

    $$ AIC = -2 \times \text{Log-likelihood} + 2p $$

    Alternatively, the extractAIC() function can calculate both AIC and BIC.
    By comparing AIC or BIC values across different models, we select the model with the smaller value.

Stepwise Regression¶

Stepwise regression is a model selection method that iteratively adds or removes predictors based on selection criteria such as AIC or BIC.

R Example¶

# Fit initial model
lm.fit <- lm(Ozone ~ Solar.R + Wind + Temp + Month, data = airquality)

# Stepwise selection using AIC and BIC
step(lm.fit, direction = "both", k = log(nrow(airquality)), trace = 0)

#create an interaction term between Wind and Temp
dat$WindTemp = dat$Wind * dat$Temp

#create an interaction term between Solor.R and Temp
dat$S3Temp = (dat$Solar-2)^3 * dat$Temp

fit.2 = lm(Ozone~ Solar.R+ Wind + Temp + Month + Day + WindTemp + S3Temp ,  data = dat)
summary(fit.2)

#Adding a few more ploynomial terms of wind

fit.3 = lm(Ozone~ Solar.R+ Wind + Temp + Month + Day + WindTemp + S3Temp + I(Wind^2) +  I(Wind^3),  data = dat)

Model selection using step function in R for linear models¶

Forward selection begins with an empty model, adding variables based on their significance until no additional relevant variables remain. It's important to note that forward selection and backward elimination may not yield the same final model.

The backward elimination method starts with a full model with all variables and then removes one variable each time to test its importance.

Bidirectional elimination is a combination of the first two methods.

In [3]:
#Forward selection 
#empty model without any variable, then adding one by one until sufficient number of variables are selected
fit0 = lm(Ozone ~ 1, data =dat)

#A model includes all other variables
fit=  lm(Ozone~., data=dat)
#Stepwise forward selection
step(fit0 , direction='forward', scope=formula(fit), trace=1)

Multicollinearity¶

Intutively: the information in the predictors is highly redundant. Some variables may contain almost all information for some other variables. There are too many predictor which may contain information for each other too much.

It refers to a scenario in which there is a strong correlation among two or more predictors. It can pose challenges for drawing meaningful conclusions about the individual contributions of each independent variable within a model, leading to less dependable statistical inferences. High multicollinearity essentially suggests that, within a regression model, at least one independent variable can be accurately predicted from the others using a linear relationship.

VIF: The variance inflation factor (VIF) can detect multicollinearity. A vif over 5 could be a problem and >10 should be remedied.

If the model has more variables/a big linear regression model, it is more likely to have multicollinearity issue.

Example: for the air quality data, if we include all variable in the linear model, is there any Multicollinearity problem?

According to the vif, there is no Multicollinearity in the model, because all vif <5.

Partial least squares¶

Reference:¶

https://learnche.org/pid/latent-variable-modelling/projection-to-latent-structures/how-the-pls-model-is-calculated

To take care of multicollinearity, PLS (Partial least squares) creates M linear combinations (from the original p predictor variables and then utilizes least squares to establish a linear regression model with these components as predictors.

Partial least squares generates $𝑀$ linear combinations ( "PLS components") from the original p predictor variables and employs least squares to construct a linear regression model, utilizing these PLS components as predictors. Different to PCR, PLS tries to find linear combinations to explain the variation in both the response variable and the predictors. PLS is a regression method combineing features of principal component analysis and multiple regression analysis to analyze the relationships between a set of predictors and a response by creating new variables. These components try to capture the maximum variance in the predictors and are also related to the response variable. Here are the steps to perform Partial Least Squares regression:

Step 1: Data Preparation

Prepare your predictors and the response. Ensure the data is clean, and handle missing values and outliers if necessary. with data scaling if needed (Optional but highly recommended). It's often a good practice to scale the variables to have zero mean and unit variance. Standardizing the variables ensures that no variable disproportionately influences the PLS model due to its scale.

Step 2: Calculation Run PLS and determine the number of components (M) to be selected. This can be done using cross-validation techniques to find the optimal number of components that minimize prediction error.

Step 3: Model Evaluation Train data Test data

Example: use mtcar data. Build a partial least squares (PLS) model to predict "mpg" using all other variables. Determine the number of components (M) to be selected. Set seed = 526.

Penalized models (Regulation)¶

The objective funtion for the least squares for a Linear Regression : $$ SSE = \sum_{i=1}^{N} { \left(y_i-\sum_{j=1}^{p}x_{ij}\beta_j \right)^2} $$

Find $\beta$s to minimize SSE ( MSE). If the predictors are highly correlated, or there are multicolinearity issues, there are some disadvantages of this method.

  1. Ridge Regression

A penalty term is added to the orinary least squre object function to control multicollinearity. The objective function of the ridge regression is

$$ \sum_{i=1}^{N} { \left(y_i-\sum_{j=1}^{p}x_{ij}\beta_j \right)^2} + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} {\beta_j}^2 $$

In a ridge regression, find $\beta$s to minimize the new objective function. The penalty is a $L_2$ penalty.

The effects of this penality: $$\hat {\bf \beta}_{ridge} = (X^TX + \lambda I)^{-1}X^TY $$.

  1. LASSO (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator)

LASSO regression encourages variable selection and reduce multicollinearity by shrinking some coefficients to zero.

The objective function of LASSO is $$ \sum_{i=1}^{N} { \left(y_i-\sum_{j=1}^{p}x_{ij}\beta_j \right)^2} + \lambda \underbrace{\sum^{p}_{j=1} \mid{\beta_j}\mid}_{\ell^1-penalisation} $$

  1. Elastic Net

Elastic Net combines L1 (Lasso) and L2 (Ridge) regularization, offering a balance between variable selection and coefficient shrinkage. It is more robust and flexible, as it allows you to control the trade-off between Ridge and Lasso regularization through a parameter ($\alpha$).

The objective function is $$ \text{minimize} \frac{1}{2n} { \left(y_i-\sum_{j=1}^{p}x_{ij}\beta_j \right)^2} + \lambda_{1} \sum_{q=1}^{p}|\beta_{qj}| + \lambda_{2} \frac{1}{2}\sum_{q=1}^{p}\beta_{qj}^{2} $$

Rewrite the penalty term into:

$$ %\text{Penalty} = (1 - \alpha) \cdot \frac{1}{2} \|\beta\|_2^2 + \alpha \cdot \|\beta\|_1 \lambda \cdot \displaystyle ((1-\alpha)/2\sum_{q=1}^{p}\beta_{qj}^{2}+\alpha\sum_{q=1}^{p}|\beta_{qj}|) $$

when $\alpha $ is 1, the penalty term becomes $$ \lambda \cdot \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^p |\beta_j| $$

when $\alpha $ is 0, the penalty term becomes $$ \lambda/2 \cdot \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^p \beta_j^2 $$

Scaling and centering is needed before we run LASSO and Ridge regression to eleminate the effects of the units.

Reference:¶

https://glmnet.stanford.edu/articles/glmnet.html

#Create train data and test data
#Split the data into a training set and a testing set

#setting seed to generate a
#reproducible random sampling


#creating training data as 85% of the dataset
library(caret)
library(keras)
library(mlbench)
library(dplyr)
library(magrittr)
library(neuralnet)

set.seed(151)


train.index  =  createDataPartition(dat$mpg, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)

#generating training dataset
#from the random_sample
training.dat =  dat[train.index, ]
 
#generating testing dataset
#from rows which are not included in training set
testing.dat  =  dat[-train.index, ]


#Train the model on the traind data
ctrl = trainControl(method="cv", number=5)

#set the space to search the tuning parameters
dgrid = data.frame( lambda =seq(0.2, 0.5, length=20), alpha=seq(0.0,1.0, length=20))

fit.01 = train(mpg~., data=training.dat, method="glmnet", tuneGrid=dgrid, trControl=ctrl, preProc=c("center", "scale"))

fit.01

 #To get the best tuning paramters 
fit.0 $ bestTune

#make prediction using the best model on the testing data
yhat = predict(fit.01, testing.dat)

#MSE of the model trained using the training data on the testing data
 mean((yhat - testing.dat$mpg)^2)
 plot(yhat, testing.dat$mpg )
